<HEADLINE> China, Japan Split Top Four in Go-Chess Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- China and Japan had secured two
spots each in the last four of the Go-chess championship after the
quarterfinals concluded here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
China has its surviving entries of seven-dan Zhou Heyang and
nine-dan Ma Xiaochun, while Japan boasted of two nine-dan players
of Koichi Kobayashi and Wang Licheng.
</P>
<P>
After the South Koreans were all eliminated in the second
round, the last eight featured five Japanese players and three
Chinese nationals.
</P>
<P>
The match between Chinese Zhou Heyang and Japanese Masaki
Takemiya lasted for seven hours, with Zhou winning the board by
two and a half pieces.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the game, Masaki said "Zhou has surprised us a lot by
upsetting reigning champion Lee Chang-ho of South Korea, but I'm
not to be his next victim."
</P>
<P>
Ma Xiaochun outwitted his Japanese peer Lin Haifeng by one and
a half pieces as the latter was exploited in his loose attacks in
the center.
</P>
<P>
Eight-dan Chao Hao of China squandered his advantages in the
contest against Satoru Kobayashi, failing to enter the last four
by one and a half pieces.
</P>
<P>
In the previous meet, Chao was also stopped by Satoru in the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
In the other all-Japanese game, Wang Licheng outplayed Cho
Chi-hum after 165 moves by slicing off a Dragon in the center,
forcing Cho leave the venue with tears full in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
The semifinals will be held in Tokyo on July 5 with Zhou Heyang
facing Satoru Kobayashi and Ma Xiaochun playing Wang Licheng.
</P>
</TEXT>
