<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, Syria Resume Trade Relation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Syria have resumed the
bilateral trade ties which were cut off in early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported that the Iraqi Trade
Ministry today signed several contracts with Syrian companies to
supply Iraq with foodstuff under the Iraq-U.N. "oil-for-food"
deal.
</P>
<P>
INA said Iraq will import a large quantity of wheat, pulses,
soap and detergents from Syria, but it gave no more details.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted a Trade Ministry official as saying
that these contracts are the first step to broaden the trade
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi trade delegation will leave for Syria soon to
reactivate trade exchange. The delegation has been invited by
Syrian Federation of Chambers of Commerce, according to the
official.
</P>
<P>
A Syrian trade delegation last month paid a first visit to
Baghdad since Iraq severed the diplomatic relations with Syria
in early 1980s because Damascus sided with Iran after the
Iraq-Iran War broke out.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the two countries further worsened since
Syrian troops joined in the 1991 Gulf War against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
