<HEADLINE> Israel Denies Israeli-Palestinian Meeting in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Israel today denied the
announcement by Egypt that Israeli and Palestinian officials
would meet in Cairo Sunday to discuss resuming the stalled peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Shai Bazak, spokesman for Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu,
also denied the claim by Palestinian officials that Israel had
agreed to halt the controversial construction of Har Homa
settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Bazak issued the denials hours after Egyptian Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa announced that senior Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators would hold a meeting in Cairo to
resume talks. This was regarded as a breakthrough in the
Egypt's recent mediation efforts to get the peace process back
on track.
</P>
<P>
Moussa's announcement came after Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak met with visiting Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat, who briefed Mubarak on the latest
contacts between Israel and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Arafat also discussed with Mubarak a number
of proposals on renewing the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Mubarak are reportedly working on a five-point plan
on resuming the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations, which calls on
Israel to freeze the settlement expansion, abide by the interim
agreement and coordinate with the PNA in deciding the scope of the
second and third Israeli troop pullbacks in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
In return, the PNA agrees to commit itself to maintaining
security cooperation with Israel and combating terrorism against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted a Palestinian official as saying that
Israel's agreement to halt the Har Homa project was conveyed
by Egyptian mediator Osama Baz, and this led to the Moussa's
announcement of holding the Israeli-Palestinian meeting in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The official added that Israel and the PNA were working on the
text of the announcement on declaring the suspension of Har Homa
project.
</P>
<P>
But Bazak denied all these claims amid mixed signals on the
Egyptian efforts in reviving the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Baz has just returned from a visit to Washington to brief the
United States officials on his shuttle mission here last week. He
is expected to return soon for another mission aimed at breaking
the deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
