<HEADLINE> Britain's Wartime Bombs Recovered from Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- British army engineers today
recovered from the sea three prototype bouncing bombs used in the
Second World War.
</P>
<P>
The bombs, designed by Barnes Wallis and used in an air attack
in 1943 to disrupt German war industries, were found in the sea
near Herne Bay on Britain's south-east coast.
</P>
<P>
"They are still intact and many of the threads and bolts are
still workable," said army spokesman Captain Alan Conroy.
</P>
<P>
The bombs, which experts say may still contain explosives, were
spotted just off the coast at low tide. They are destined for
military museums once they have been made safe and cleaned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
