<HEADLINE> Israel to Host International Economic Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Israel has decided to host a
large international economic conference in 1998 as part of
celebrations of 50th birthday of the Jewish state, reported
bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
An organizing committee is currently being established, which
is to be chaired by Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be designed to provide leading financial
organizations and potential investors with information regarding
Israel's economic program for the coming years, and to attract
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The event organizers intend to invite around 600 guests to
the conference, including the heads of multinational corporations
and some of the world business community's leading investors.
The speakers at the event will present Israel's economic plans
for the 21st century
</P>
<P>
Several large conference organizing companies from around the
world have already been contacted and a decision is expected to be
announced in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem is the venue of an annual international business
conference. But due to the low ebb of the peace process in
the Middle East, the participants in the 1996 conference were
considerably less than the previous three years. Some Arab
states boycotted the conference.
</P>
<P>
Many Arab countries have also voiced their opposition to
extend invitation to Israel for the 1997 Middle East and North
African Economic summit to be held in Qatar later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
