<HEADLINE> Egypt: No Formal Palestinian-Israeli Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
today ruled out Palestinian-Israeli experts' meeting here Sunday
would be a resumption of formal peace talks that collapsed two
months ago.
</P>
<P>
"It would differ from the normal negotiating track between the
them," the minister told reporters, adding Egypt will attend the
meeting as an observer.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have their track and
certain committees," he added. But this meeting was decided upon
after Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat
Friday met an advisor to Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
who conveyed some Israeli ideas to bring closer views.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks broke down in March when
Israel began construction of a new Jewish settlement in disputed
Arab East Jerusalem. Palestinians conditioned the resumption of
negotiations on halting the project.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's meeting will tackle the Jewish settlements and other
important issues on the Mideast peace process, said Moussa earlier
following a brief meeting here this morning between Arafat and
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
The summit, the second in four days, took place on the heels of
Netanyahu's declaration of plans to retain 60 percent of the West
Bank lands in his envisioned final peace settlement on the
Palestinian track.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Sobieh, Palestine's permanent delegate to the Arab
League, who attended the meeting, said that Arafat briefed Mubarak
on dangers of Netanyahu's plan, which he termed as a "flagrant
violation" of Oslo and other signed accords.
</P>
<P>
"The 40 percent (of the West Bank) Israel will give to the
Palestinians represents separate parts (of the occupied lands),
with Israel keeping greater Jerusalem," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's plan, which was revealed early this week, includes
a partial Israeli withdrawal from 40 percent of the West Bank and
strengthening the Israeli presence in Jerusalem and the Jewish
settlement in the West Bank. The Palestinians have rejected it.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said instead of fresh U.S. suggestions to bring closer
Palestinian and Israeli view points, there are only Israeli
proposals now.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has taken an important role in mediating an end to the
crisis between the Palestinians and Israelis after U.S. Mideast
coordinator Dennis Ross's shuttle trips tappered off.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's top aid Osama el-Baz, upon return from his five-day
visit to the U.S., said he briefed Washington on his shuttle tours
between Israel and the PNA designed to bring them back to the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Egypt and the Palestinians were working
on a five-point plan which includes a freeze on any change in the
status of Jerusalem and a ban on Jewish settlement of the West
Bank for a "sufficient period" of time.
</P>
<P>
In return, the Palestinians would give a firm commitment to
address Israel's security demands, they added.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Egyptian efforts, the gap remained wide, especially
on the question of Jewish settlement, according to the
sources. Netanyahu has refused to stop the new construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
