<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Wins Seat in Irish Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein, political wing of the
Irish Republican Army (IRA), has won a seat in the new Irish
parliament, reports from Dublin said today.
</P>
<P>
Its candidate Caoimhghin O Caolain won a seat in the border
constituency of Cavan Monaghan in the Irish general election which
was held on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein's election victory, its first since 1981, will
reinforce the party's demand for entry to talks on the future of
Northern Ireland, observers said.
</P>
<P>
It is barred by Britain and Ireland from Northern Ireland peace
talks because the IRA has not restored a ceasefire it broke in
February 1996 with a huge bomb in London. But Sinn Fein insists it
is committed to peace and demands entry to the talks.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein also fielded candidates in Northern Ireland in
British elections. Party leader Gerry Adams and senior strategist
Martin McGuinness were elected to Britain's House of Commons in
the May 1 election, but have refused to take their seats as this
would entail swearing allegiance to the Queen.
</P>
<P>
The party decided in 1986 to abandon its long-standing policy
of boycotting the Irish parliament, but until now has failed to
capture any seats in subsequent elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
