<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Acting Premier: Crimes Must Be Attacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Acting Prime Minister
Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah today called for tighter security
following an assassination attempt on a parliamentary member.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a National Assembly session, Al-Sabah, also the
foreign minister, said the murder attempt on Abdallah Al-Neibari
Friday was "not done by Kuwaiti hands," but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
He called on security authorities to "foil schemes by
perpetrators who wanted to incite discords in the country."
</P>
<P>
He also urged the Kuwaiti people to stay calm and refrain from
inciting further tension.
</P>
<P>
Al-Neibari, a leading liberal member of the parliament, was
shot and injured by machine-gun fire along with his wife yesterday
south of Kuwait City while they were driving home from their
week-end villa near the Saudi border.
</P>
<P>
All the Kuwaiti people were shocked by the attack, the acting
prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kuwaiti parliament which was originally scheduled to
discuss the state security carried out an open session to discuss
the gun shooting incident under the demands of 30 parliamentary
members.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti newspapers today all condemned the assassination
attempt in their front pages and described the crime as an ugly
act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
