<DOCNO> XIE19970608.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Chief Stresses Stability, Development in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Organization of African
Unity (OAU) Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim said here today
that the challenges facing the OAU and the continent in general
are still political stability and economic development at
present.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief, during a two-day stop-over in his native
country Tanzania from Harare, Zimbabwe, where he attended the
organization's 33rd summit meeting, told a press conference that
from now on, the OAU will strongly oppose any group or people who
topple a democratically elected government in Africa.
</P>
<P>
For political stability in the continent, "there must be a
wind of change to ensure democracy prevails in Africa," he said,
adding that, "we have rejected the Sierra Leone military's
takeover."
</P>
<P>
He said, "our stand also still remains the same with regard to
Buyoya's administration in Burundi, who must fulfill conditions
set forth by the Great Lakes region leaders before sanctions
could be lifted on his administration."
</P>
<P>
Salim further said that there is need to strengthen the OAU's
conflict resolution mechanism unit through increased
contributions by member states to reduce donor reliance.
</P>
<P>
Africa must respond quickly to conflicts at their early stages
rather than waiting to intervene when fighting has started, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief said that another priority area in Africa is
economic development, with stress placed on integration of
economies.
</P>
<P>
"For Africa to be competitive in the economic scene, we must
be serious on integration," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said: "it is high time we must be practical. The OAU will
strengthen its support to such regional bodies as the SADC,
COMESA and ECOWAS in this direction."
</P>
<P>
On the role of non-governmental organizations (NGOs), the OAU
chief said it should also be strengthened, adding that the NGOs
had greatly contributed to the development process in the
continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
