<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The Second Tunis International Automobile Exhibition
opened today at the Exhibition Palace in the town of Al-Karm, 15
kilometers east of the Tunisian capital.
</P>
<P>
This 8-day exhibition is participated in by world
automobile-manufacturing companies, in addition to more than 112
Tunisian and foreign factories producing automobile components and
spare parts.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition contains the most up-to-date types of cars and
industrial vehicles produced by world companies in Europe, the
U.S. and Japan, specimens of cars, buses and trucks assembled in
Tunisia, Algeria and Libya, in addition to automobile components
and spare parts made in Tunis, Algeria, Morocco, France, Italy
Spain, Germany, Turkey and India.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is intended to promote cooperation between
Tunisian manufacturers of automobile components and world
automobile companies, and further integration of the Arab-Maghreb
countries in automobile manufacture.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's Akkuyu nuclear power plant bid has to be
delayed for two months, local newspaper Daily News reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted informed sources from the energy and natural
resources ministry as saying that the decision was made on a
request of one of the three tenderers.
</P>
<P>
Two of the prospective consortia are already prepared to seal
their bids but the third one has requested a delay for unknown
reasons, said Ugur Dogan, a consultant with the ministry.
</P>
<P>
However, Dogan failed to give the names of the three bidding
companies.
</P>
<P>
While saying that it was unfair to reveal the construction
financing before the bid was submitted, he told the paper that
the project, which is located in Mersin, a coast city in southern
Turkey, is estimated to cost around 2.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the safety of the nuclear power, the official said
that the experience of those developed countries had proved that
it was safe to generate power through nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
Some environmental protection organizations have protested the
government's program to build nuclear power plant for fear of
pollution and health problems.
</P>
<P>
As an energy-starving country, Turkey has to import oil and
natural gas to meet its domestic needs every year.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraq and Syria have resumed the bilateral trade ties
which were cut off in early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported that the Iraqi Trade
Ministry today signed several contracts with Syrian companies to
supply Iraq with foodstuff under the Iraq-U.N. "oil-for-food"
deal.
</P>
<P>
INA said Iraq will import a large quantity of wheat, pulses,
soap and detergents from Syria, but it gave no more details.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted a Trade Ministry official as saying
that these contracts are the first step to broaden the trade
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi trade delegation will leave for Syria soon to
reactivate trade exchange. The delegation has been invited by
Syrian Federation of Chambers of Commerce, according to the
official.
</P>
<P>
A Syrian trade delegation last month paid a first visit to
Baghdad since Iraq severed the diplomatic relations with Syria
in early 1980s because Damascus sided with Iran after the
Iraq-Iran War broke out.
</P>
<P>
The relations between the two countries further worsened since
Syrian troops joined in the 1991 Gulf War against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel has decided to host a large international
economic conference in 1998 as part of celebrations of 50th
birthday of the Jewish state, reported bi-weekly Israel Business
Today.
</P>
<P>
An organizing committee is currently being established, which
is to be chaired by Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be designed to provide leading financial
organizations and potential investors with information regarding
Israel's economic program for the coming years, and to attract
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The event organizers intend to invite around 600 guests to
the conference, including the heads of multinational corporations
and some of the world business community's leading investors.
The speakers at the event will present Israel's economic plans
for the 21st century
</P>
<P>
Several large conference organizing companies from around the
world have already been contacted and a decision is expected to be
announced in the near future.
</P>
