<HEADLINE> Clinton Announces Plan for Hate Crimes Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Said
Saturday that it is time for Americans "to mount an all-out
assault on hate crime," and called for convening a White House
conference this fall to address the threat.
</P>
<P>
In his weekly radio address today, Clinton says the conference
will seek to "confront the dark forces of division that still
exist" in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno is reviewing the current hate
crimes' laws on the books, and in preparation of the conference
will determine ways the federal government can put in place a
"vigorous plan of action" to counter the menace.
</P>
<P>
Clinton says crimes "committed solely because the victims have
a different skin color or a different faith or are gays or
lesbians, leave deep scars not only on the victims, but also on
our larger community."
</P>
<P>
The conference is planned for November 10 at the White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
