<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Coup Leader Explains Power Takeover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's coup leader Major
Johnny Koroma has said the soldiers seized power in order to end
the six-year civil war in the country, according to a report
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
In his first formal interview with foreign press on Friday
since the May 25 coup, Koroma said that the rebel Revolutionary
United Front (RUF), which launched the civil war in 1991, and the
army were tired of fighting and wanted peace, which is the reason
that they are now standing together.
</P>
<P>
He also said he planned to form a broad-based government in
which rebels played a full part.
</P>
<P>
"Our intention is to form a broad-based government of national
unity fully incorporating the RUF to restore everlasting peace
and sanity throughout the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Koroma said: "we are committed to the democratic process
and we want elections but there are problems that we have to
solve. We must make sure that these problems are ironed out before
there will be an election," adding that this would take at least
18 months.
</P>
<P>
Koroma also accused ousted civilian President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah, whose election last year ended four years of military
rule in Sierra Leone, of undermining the honor and dignity of the
armed forces by turning a militia of Kamajor traditional hunters
against them.
</P>
<P>
By "arming and poisoning the minds" of the Kamajor, the
Kabbah government was deliberately trying to "sabotage the
legitimacy of the military", he said.
</P>
<P>
"This situation led to the persistent slaughter of soldiers
nationwide," Koroma said, adding that in spite of repeated
complaints, the past government refused to take necessary action.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the soldiers had to overthrow the government
by means of coup because they wanted to "prevent the country from
descending into tribal and regional warfare".
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that the formation of the civil defense
forces on regional and tribal lines would "no doubt have created
disaster for this nation".
</P>
<P>
As for the RUF rebels, who flooded into the capital Freetown
after the coup, Koroma said the coup organizers were able to
control them.
</P>
<P>
"They (the rebels) are committed to peace in Sierra Leone and
the RUF has assured the new military regime through the RUF
leader, Corporal Foday Sankoh, that they are committed to peace,"
Koroma said.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh was reportedly discharged from the RUF leadership by
his followers after an alleged house arrest last May in Nigeria.
The coup leaders have appealed the Nigerian government to send
him back.
</P>
<P>
The coup has been widely condemned among the international
community. The west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG
has started military intervention to restore Kabbah's government
in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the report, dissident army officers have
said they will not accept Kabbah back.
</P>
<P>
The situation still remains tense in Freetown and many people
have been fleeing for fears that ECOMOG bombardment might take
place this weekend.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between west African countries and the military
are reportedly underway for a peaceful settlement of the crisis
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
