<HEADLINE> Kuwait Arrests Kuwaitis, Iranians for Shooting MP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Three Kuwaitis and two
Iranians were arrested on charge of attempting to kill parliament
member Abdullah Al-Neibari and his wife, Kuwaiti Interior Ministry
confirmed today in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's public relations department said in a statement
that "the security authorities have managed in a record time to
identify and arrest the suspects who will be referred to the
public prosecution for further interrogation."
</P>
<P>
"The five suspects were arrested within 24 hours after the
crime took place (shortly before night fall Friday) and the
security authorities identified their nationalities and the role
of every one of them" in the assassination attempt, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
It did not disclose their names, ages and identities, but said
they were referred to the public prosecution along with the
vehicles and tools used in the crime.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti cabinet met today to discuss the incident and praised
the interior ministry for the speedy apprehension of the suspects.
</P>
<P>
Abdallah Al-Neibari and his wife were shot and injured by
machine-gun fire in south of Kuwait city Friday while they were
driving home from their week-end villa near the Saudi border.
</P>
<P>
He is a leading liberal member of the 50-seat parliament and
was head of the public fund protection committee, an offshoot of
the financial and economic affairs committee in the 1992
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah Saturday called on security
authorities to foil schemes by perpetrators who want to incite
discords in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that "what happened was not carried out by Kuwaiti
hands. It is a strife that should be uprooted before anything
else."
</P>
<P>
He urged the Kuwaiti people to stay calm and refrain from
inciting further tension.
</P>
<P>
All the Kuwaiti people are shocked by the attack, the acting
prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary Speaker Ahmad Al-Saadoun urged the government to
combat corruption and praised Al-Neibari as "one of those who
stood against bids to transform Kuwait into a hostage for thieves
of public funds."
</P>
<P>
Al-Saadoun accused corrupt people and thieves of public funds
of being behind the attack, adding that "this is a message to the
Kuwaiti people and to the honest." 
</P>
</TEXT>
