<HEADLINE> Nepal to Preserve Interests of Indigenous Communities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government is making
preparations for setting up separate centers for the development
and rehabilitation of indigenous and backward communities, local
sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State Mahesh Chaudhari disclosed the government's
plan to preserve the interests of backward communities while
opening a general convention of the Nepal Indigenous People's
Federation here Saturday, federation officials said.
</P>
<P>
The minister on the occasion also expressed his regrets that
the country has not developed on a sound basis because of the
backwardness of indigenous people, they said.
</P>
<P>
Official demographic statistics show that there are 61 groups
of indigenous and tribal people in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that the indigenous groups, with different
languages from each other, account for about 35 percent of the
country's population of 22 million.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the general convention from organizations
representing various ethnic groups urged the government to take
concrete measures to preserve indigenous culture like compiling
dictionaries of indigenous languages and writing history of the
indigenous people, the sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
