<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Cost Drives Nigerians Away From Hospitals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- High cost of medical treatment,
time-wasting in outpatient wards and widespread demand for
pre-treatment deposits are driving more and more Nigerians away
from hospitals.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the Sunday Times found that seven out of 10
persons interviewed in Lagos said they would rather consult
friends, spiritualists or roadside drug sellers than go to
hospitals when they are ill.
</P>
<P>
Professor Olusoga Sofola from the college of medicine,
university of Lagos, said that patients had become so few that
there were not enough of them with whom to train medical students
at the college.
</P>
<P>
At the Lagos State University Teaching Hospital, patients now
have to deposit 20,000 naira (about 235 U.S. dollars) for any
surgical operations involving blood transfusion. This is a rise
of 100 percent over the charges last year.
</P>
<P>
In some hospitals, patients who fail to raise the required
deposits are sent away.
</P>
<P>
When patients turn to roadside drug sellers, the chances are
that they have a possibility of 70 percent to buy fake drugs,
according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Noniface Oye Adeniran, an official from the Nigerian
Medical Association, however, defended the hospitals' high
charges.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the situation to the poor financing of hospitals by
government.
</P>
<P>
Further more, he said, doctors operate within the same
economic climate as other companies. When the cost of everything
is going up, it is not fair to blame hospitals alone for rising
charges over services.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper suggested that solution lies in the need for a
national health insurance scheme and a review of the country's primary
health care program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
