<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Plans Beautification Scheme for Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A batch of 50 lanterns arrived in
 Hong Kong today from Foshan city in Guangdong province for the
Urban Council's Beautification Scheme to mark Hong Kong's return
to the Motherland.
</P>
<P>
According to the Urban Council, about 200 lantern masters and
workers at a handicraft factory in Foshan are in full swing
trussing their innovative art pieces, including nine giant dragons
 plus 400 decorative lanterns.
</P>
<P>
The nine giant dragon lanterns would be mounted at the Hong
Kong Cultural Center Open Air Square in Tsim Sha Tsui in Kowloon
and will be shipped to Hong Kong for the Urban Council's City
Beautification Scheme to commemorate Hong Kong's handover.
</P>
<P>
Elaine Chung lai-kwok, director of the Urban Services of the
Urban Council, said that the Foshan Folk Art Research Agency will
be able to deliver all lanterns in time to tie in with the
scheme's switching-on ceremony on June 25 evening.
</P>
<P>
She said that the lanterns together with other large-scale
lightings, will form the first part of the 14-million HK dollar
City Beautification Scheme.
</P>
<P>
The scheme also includes erection of a grand Chinese gate at
Salisbury Garden, a well-decorated Chinese theatrical stage at
Statue Square, a splendid doom adorned with illuminated sea
creatures at Hong Kong Space Museum and a beautiful fairy
sprinkling flowers at the City Hall.
</P>
<P>
The Wan Chai Cross Harbor Tunnel Approach amenity area will be
transformed into a Chinese garden featuring a fountain, rookeries,
 flowers and plants in specially designed pots.  
</P>
</TEXT>
