<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Farmer-Businessmen Interested In Farming Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Some farmers who turned to
business in Zhejiang Province, in east China, have shown a renewed
interest in their former profession -- but this time, they plan to
develop more by hiring laborers instead of working like they did
before.
</P>
<P>
At least 100,000 former farmers in the province have gone
elsewhere to grow farm produce and provide badly needed
by-products. The new move started with mushroom growers in
Qingyuan County, where land was insufficient and the price of
mushrooms too low, so farmers decided to try their luck in the
Shanghai suburbs in 1993.
</P>
<P>
They got land contracts for land and grew mushrooms there at
about the same cost but sold them at a much higher price,
encouraging others. Now over 10,000 of them are making a good
profit growing mushrooms and raising fish, both of which sell well
in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
In the late 1970s, farmers from Zhejiang took the lead in China
in going elsewhere to look for job opportunities, and more than
two million of them made a lot of money that way. Some of them
went back to their villages and set up businesses, becoming
businesspeople overnight.
</P>
<P>
These farmer-entrepreneurs, of which there are estimated to be
about 200,000, have helped improve the province's agriculture by
expanding the scale of farming by integrating agriculture,
industry and trade.
</P>
<P>
One of those businessmen working in other provinces is Xie
Fujiang, in Huzhou, who is a fairly typical example. He signed a
30-year land-use contract for about 86 ha earlier this year on a
state farm in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province to grow
soybeans.
</P>
<P>
Xie paid the farm nearly 640,000 yuan for miscellaneous fees,
but says, "I believe the fertile land will repay all my investment
in two years, if everything goes smoothly." He plans to sell the
soybeans in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
Some other businesspeople even go abroad. One edible fungus
company has bought about 1.6 ha of land in Seattle to grow
mushroom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
