<HEADLINE> France Sends War Materials to Congo Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 8 (Xinhua) -- France is reportedly sending war
materials to the Congo Republic after one French soldier was
killed and five others wounded Saturday evening in a skirmish with
"uncontrollable armed elements" in Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry did not specify which kinds of war
materials were being sent or from where they were sent.
</P>
<P>
Agence France Presse (AFP) reported that they are apparently
Vehicles of Avant-Blinde used by French army to transport soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The vehicles can be sent either from France or from the Central
African Republic or Gabon, where France maintains military bases.
</P>
<P>
About 450 French soldiers are now deployed in Brazzaville,
originally for the purpose of evacuating French nationals from
neighboring Kinshasa, the capital of the Democratic Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
Violent fighting continued in Brazzaville today between the
supporters of Congolese President Pascal Lissouba and those of
former President Denis Sassou-Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers supporting Sassou-Nguesso today claimed the
capture of the central government building, the treasury and two
strategic highlands overlooking Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Radio France Internationale, the former
president said that he would accept a ceasefire if the government
admitted that he had been self-defending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
