<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq's Power System Close to Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's power generation system,
which is working at only 40 to 50 percent of the capacity due to
lack of spare parts, is close to collapse, the English-language
newspaper Baghdad Observer reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper in an article quoted Kareem Wahid Hassan,
director-general of Dora power station in the capital, as
saying that "only 40 to 50 percent of the capacity of the
country's whole power generation system was regained."
</P>
<P>
He told reporters recently that Iraq has used up most of the
spare parts in government storage in order to maintain such
capacity of power generation.
</P>
<P>
Over 2.5 million Iraqi families suffer the shortage of
electricity, Adnan Abdul Majeed, Minister of Industry and
Minerals told a press conference last week.
</P>
<P>
He blamed the U.S. for blocking the approval of contracts
submitted to the U.N. Sanctions Committee for purchasing power
spare parts.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal singed by the U.N. and Iraq last year,
which allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil
over six months to buy food and other supplies, allocates 36
million dollars for the purchase of spare parts for electricity
generation.
</P>
<P>
Hassen said the amount allocated by the deal to purchase
power spare parts covered only 4 percent of the total needs of
Iraq's power grid. However, none of them has arrived in the
country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under stringent sanctions imposed by the
U.N. Security Council since 1990 for its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than 90 percent of the country's
power stations, which were heavily bombed in the 1991 Gulf War,
have been rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
Iraq needs a high electricity load to cope with domestic
demand fueled by a one-third rise in population. Its power
generation should be increased to 18,000 megawatts by the end of
the year 2000, said the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
