<HEADLINE> Beijing Encourages Residents to Buy, Read More Books </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Urban families with a collection of
2,000 copies of books and suburban families with a collection of
more than 1,000 copies of books in the capital of China will have
a chance to be awarded for their love of books.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Federation of Women and Dazhong Reading
Society have jointly sponsored a selection of families and
individuals fond of collecting and reading books.
</P>
<P>
The selection began in April and will last through the
year. 100 families and ten individuals will become "zhuangyuan"
(No.1 contestant in the imperial examination in old China) at the
end of the selection.
</P>
<P>
The activity is aimed at promoting the collecting and reading
of good books among the citizens and further improving their
quality, according to Wu Xiuping, vice-chairman of the Municipal
Federation of Women.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent investigation, the percentage of urban
Chinese residents' spending on cultural consumption was ten
percent in 1993, 13.5 percent in 1994 and 18.5 percent in
1995. During the same period, the spending on food had been
steadily around 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
The purchase and storage of books has become a necessity for
residents in the capital city. A discounted-priced book fair held
here this month received more than 200,000 customers within the
first five days and reported a daily business volume of two
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
A weekend reading activity was held in the city last year,
drawing 300,000 families within nine months.
</P>
<P>
According to the Dazhong Reading Society, a number of ordinary
urban families have a collection of between 4,000 and 5,000 copies
of books. Even in remote mountainous Pinggu County, there are more
than 10,000 families with a collection of more than 100 books
each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
