<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, U.N. Exchange Letters to Renew Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and the U.N. on Saturday
night exchanged the letters to renew the "oil-for-food" deal
signed by the two sides last May, the official Iraqi News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nizar Hamdoun, Iraq's permanent envoy to the U.N. and Hans
Korel, U.N. Under Secretary-General for legal affairs exchanged
the letters in the United Nations. Whereby, a six-month extension
of the "oil-for-food" deal has been okeyed as of today.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council agreed Wednesday to let Iraq sell oil
for another six months to buy food and medicine. The 15-member
council voted unanimously to allow another 2.1 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil sales.
</P>
<P>
The deal, signed by Iraq and the U.N. in May last year and came
into effect on December 10, expired on Saturday. It allows Iraq to
sell 2 billion dollars worth of oil over 180 days on a renewable
basis to buy food and other daily necessities urgently needed in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been hit seriously by the sanctions imposed by the
U.N. Security Council after its invasion of Kuwait in August,
1990.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has refused to lift sanctions entirely
until it is fully convinced that Iraq has destroyed its weapons of
mass destruction and made a full disclosure to U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Over the coming weeks, the Iraqi government will forward a
distribution plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
