</P>
<P>
-- President Bill Clinton ordered a Justice Department review
of laws against hate crimes and said he will call a conference.
</P>
<P>
-- States have less that a month to meet the federal deadline
for enacting a plan to carry out welfare reform, yet California,
home to one-fifth of the nation's welfare recipients, is nowhere
near a consensus on crucial components of its plan.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Conflicts within the Republican Party will clearly be on
display in the coming weeks as the Congressional tax committees
begin drafting legislation to carry out the 135-billion dollars
tax reduction included in the bipartisan balanced budget
agreement. Social conservatives will want to cut taxes for
families, while economic conservatives seek a reduction in the
capital gains tax.
</P>
<P>
-- An ethics commission charged with recommending actions on
human cloning to President Clinton called for a legislative ban on
attempts to clone people. Such a ban would restrain private groups
that get no Federal financing for cloning research. The Government
has a moratorium in place now to ban human clones, but that
affects only researchers supported by Federal money. the
moratorium began on March 4. 
</P>
