<HEADLINE> Qatar Seeks Foreign Investment in Chemical Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Qatar will seek foreign partners
for 15 medium-scale chemical projects worth 3 billion
U.S. dollars at the upcoming Middle East and North Africa (MENA)
economic summit, according to a press release reaching here today
from Qatar.
</P>
<P>
"We will offer these projects as joint ventures and seek
direct foreign investment from multinational corporations which
will attend the MENA conference," said the press statement by
Qatar's Ministry of Energy and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Qatar expected that between 2,500 and 3,000 businessmen from
Asia, Middle East, Europe and the U.S. will take part in the
summit which will take place in Doha, the Qatari capital, in
November.
</P>
<P>
"Our focus will be on recommending those downstream projects
which have wide application in the plastic industry and markets in
all parts of the world," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has the world's third largest reserves of gas after
Russia and Iran.
</P>
<P>
So far, it has been working on major liquefied natural gas and
other cost-intensive petrochemical projects to tap the field. But
it is giving a shift in policy to develop medium and small
industry to produce value-added products. 
</P>
