<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebei Renovating Historical Buildings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- North China's cultural
relic-rich province, Hebei, has invested some 200 million yuan
since 1990 to renovate local historical buildings.
</P>
<P>
To date some 240 projects on historical buildings under state
or provincial protection have been completed, while other 20 are
being undertaken.
</P>
<P>
The projects including those on the imperial summer resort of
the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) in Chengde in the northern part of
Hebei and the eastern and western imperial tombs of the dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Local relics officials say that all the renovation plans have
been approved by leading experts and implemented by skillful
artisans.
</P>
<P>
"We have tried our best to use original materials and
traditional techniques to restore the buildings to their original
features," the officials say, adding that such renovation is time
consuming.
</P>
<P>
For instance, it took 100 artisans to work for five years to
renovate some 20 buildings in the Longfu temple in Qingxiling (the
Western Imperial Tomb of the Qing Dynasty).
</P>
<P>
Hebei has 12,000 historical sites, 58 of them are under state
protection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
