<HEADLINE> Iran to Join Convention Against Chemical Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Parliament today approved
a bill that allows its government to join the convention against
development, production, stockpiling and using of chemical
weapons.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Tehran Radio reported it today without giving
any details about the bill.
</P>
<P>
The bill came a month after Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani rejected U.S. charges that Iran has been engaged in
the production of chemical weapons, terming it as "a sheer
allegation."
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said that Iran would never think of having or
employing chemical weapons since "We have had such a terrifying
experience" during the eight years of Iran-Iraq war (1980-88).
</P>
<P>
In Washington, Iran's permanent representative to the U.N.,
Kamal Kharazi, also rejected the U.S. allegation, saying
"Washington has once again resorted to baseless claims in an
irresponsible manner in connection with the peaceful activities
of the Iranian chemical industries."
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran is a signatory to the Treaty on
Non-Proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction and a victim of
these weapons during its war with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iran rejects all allegation on any plan to produce chemical
weapons in the country, Kharazi added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
