<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Beer Makers Targeting Chinese Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 8 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's giant breweries are
targeting the Chinese beer market which is quickly emerging as the
world's largest, according to industry sources here.
</P>
<P>
Oriental Brewery (OB), one of the biggest breweries in South
Korea, has decided recently to establish a locally-incorporated
firm in China, and Chosun Brewery of the popular Hite brand is
expected to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
OB is currently looking to take over a brewery in China's
Shandong Province with an investment of 78.65 million
U.S. dollars, and to establish a plant with an annual production
capacity of 100,000 kiloliters.
</P>
<P>
"OB is seeking to develop one or two local brands for initial
marketing popular OB lager beer sometime next year," one industry
official said.
</P>
<P>
Chosun is seeking to gain entry into the Chinese market through
a Chinese liquor company in which Bohae Distillery Co. has
invested. Chosun recently took over Bohae to enter the white
spirit market.
</P>
<P>
Chosun will take over a brewery in China with a production
capacity of 100,000 kiloliters, and transfer to the brewery the
manufacturing systems in its Seoul plant.
</P>
<P>
The reason for such a rush to get into the Chinese beer market
is obvious, considering the demand in the world's most populous
country has shown a continuous increase in recent years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970608.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Scientists Propose to Monitor Genetic Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- India's top scientists have
expressed their concern over possible abuse of genetic research
and have called for creation of an apex national bioethics
organization (NBO) to monitor research being carried out with
human genetic material.
</P>
<P>
They warned in a recently released document that the latest
advances in genetics research "raise ethical, social, cultural and
legal issues with significant long-term implications for
humanity."
</P>
<P>
"While genetic studies may provide powerful tools, they are
also prone to abuses which could threaten society," the scientists
said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the apex NBO, the document suggested setting up
genetic testing laboratories in each state for providing
diagnostic service and to carry out research on the genetic basis
of unusual diseases encountered in India.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
