<DOCNO> XIE19970608.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Render Continued Support for China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing internal reforms of the
World Bank will help strengthen its cooperation with China, the
international financial body's largest client, a senior bank
official said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to serve China better still. I think China will remain
as important as it is today," Pieter Bottelier, chief of the World
Bank's resident mission in China, told Xinhua in an interview
recently.
</P>
<P>
The major field offices of the World Bank, including the office
in China, will be reinforced after the structural reorganization
inside the Bank, he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the major offices will have a greater
decision-making power and more responsibility, adding that "we
hope to become more efficient, quicker and more tuned-in to
China's needs."
</P>
<P>
Bottelier said that internal reforms of the international
financial body will give its China office greater flexibility in
dealing with the designing and implementation of World Bank-aided
projects and in solving problems.
</P>
<P>
"It's also our intention to broaden the range of financial
instruments available to support China's development," he said.
</P>
<P>
After he completes his term of office as chief of the China
mission and returns to the Bank's headquarters in Washington D.C.,
he will continue to promote cooperation with China, he added.
</P>
<P>
After its World Bank membership was resumed in May 1980, China
has since 1993 become the international financial body's single
largest client with an annual borrowings standing between 2.5 and
three billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics of the World Bank show that the
international financial body has, to date, lent a total of more
than 26.8 billion US dollars to 180 projects in China, which cover
almost all economic sectors.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Bottelier said that as the International Development
Association (IDA), the Bank's lending arm for cheap loans, has
limited financial resources, the Bank will arrange more
co-financing and cross-financing for China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970608.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank to Render Continued Support for China  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The World Bank's relationship with China is very effective and
we think it is important that the World Bank continues to support
social development and poverty elimination in China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Chinese economy, Bottelier said: "The macro
economic situation at this point is very very strong, as inflation
has gone down to well below six percent and the economy has been
growing at a high but sustainable level."
</P>
<P>
He said that the economic macro-control measures of the Chinese
government in the past three and more years have been effective
and the moderately-tight fiscal and monetary policies have
produced the desired results, enabling the national economy to
head for a successful soft landing last year.
</P>
<P>
Bottelier recalled that the Chinese economy was overheated when
he came to Beijing as chief of the World Bank's mission in China
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
This year, China's economic situation will improve further and
the major economic indicators will, very likely, be better than
expected, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
China has constantly seen its economy grow nearly ten percent
annually in recent years. Meanwhile, it has effectively brought
inflation under control, cutting the annual increase rate of the
retail price index to 6.1 percent last year, down from 21.7
percent in 1994 and 14.8 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
China has set this year's economic growth rate at around eight
percent and the inflation control target at six percent. In the
first quarter of this year, the Chinese economy was up 9.4 percent
while the retail price index rose 2.6 percent on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the past achievements, China should further improve
its fiscal situation, accelerate the pace to reform state-owned
enterprises and the process of commercializing the state-owned
banks, and create more job opportunities, in order to guarantee a
healthy and long-term economic development, Bottelier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
