<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 08:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israelis, Palestinians to Resume Dialogue Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli-Palestinian dialogue,
aimed at renewing full-scale peace talks, is scheduled to take
place in the Egyptian capital of Cairo this afternoon under the
Egyptian auspices.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the arrangement was confirmed in a
late-night telephone conversation Saturday between Israeli
cabinet secretary Danny Naveh and Egyptian presidential adviser
Osama Al-Baz.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli team will consist of Naveh, Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu's senior aide Yitzhak Molcho, and his new
political adviser Uzi Arad, as well as Foreign Ministry adviser
Ya'acov Bardugo.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian initiative was almost scuttled when Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa announced the meeting prematurely, prompting
both sides to issue clarifications before the arrangement was
finally set.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) said Saturday that it
was encouraged by Egyptian mediation efforts to get political
talks with Israel started again and hoped there would be
practical progress in today's Cairo talks.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial Palestinian sources said that by sending
representatives to Cairo, Israel was not ruling out a slowdown in
settlement building, as this possibility was what made the meeting
in Cairo possible.
</P>
<P>
However, Nabil Abu Rudeineh, adviser to PNA President Yasser
Arafat, said that, "The only progress is that there will be a
meeting and that we have better contacts with Israel."
</P>
<P>
"But there is not any agreement concerning anything," he
said. "Nothing has been agreed upon, and we hope we might
achieve something," added the PNA adviser.
</P>
<P>
Abu Rudeineh also remarked on the close coordination of the
United States and Egyptian positions as something positive in
light of Arafat's previous charges that the U.S. sided with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
A flurry of consultations between Israeli and Arab leaders and
among Arabs themselves has boosted the view that a way out of the
current deadlock is pending, and that this has to involve a
cessation or slowdown of Israeli settlement building in disputed
areas, including the Har Homa (or Jabal Abu Ghoneim) project in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a slowdown would most likely be accompanied by
acceleration of final-status talks between the Israelis and
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian sources said that Arafat conferred with Netanyahu's
senior aide and Israeli General Security Service chief Ami Ayalon
Friday; he then went to Cairo Saturday to meet with President
Hosni Mubarak, and today he is expected in Jordan for talks with
the Jordanian monarch King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said that Egypt has proposed a five-point
plan, which includes a freeze on any change in the status of
Jerusalem and a ban on Jewish settlement building in the West
Bank for "a sufficient period."
</P>
<P>
In return, the Palestinians would make a firm commitment to
meeting Israel's security demands, they added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Saturday Israeli media reported that Israel agreed on
a temporary halt in the construction of Jewish settlements in
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel Television Channel 1 reported that Israel and the PNA
were trying to reach agreement on the duration of a construction
freeze on Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, as
well as in Jerusalem's Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Israel would begin the work on a
housing project of 3,000 units for Palestinian Jerusalemites
"near Har Homa" immediately and would suspend work at the area
earmarked for Jewish residents as soon as the infrastructure
there is completed.
</P>
<P>
However, the report was denied by Netanyahu's spokesman, Shai
Bazak, who said the building at Har Homa would not stop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
