<DOCNO> XIE19970608.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Taxi Firm Ambitious to Match Hertz Company of US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai Dazhong Taxi Co. Ltd. is
resolved to build itself into a firm that can stand up to Hertz
Company of the United States in the aspects of taxi and car rental
service.
</P>
<P>
Yang Guoping, chairman of the Board of Dazhong Taxi Co. Ltd.,
said his company would strive to expand business in the coming
years and build a fleet of 10,000 taxi cars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Only through operating business on a fairly large scale and
expanding market share remarkably can we achieve greater economic
benefits amid fierce market competitions," said Yang.
</P>
<P>
China has seen fast expansion of taxi service as it has a quick
development in cities over the past years. In Shanghai, which has
a population of 13 million, there are some 560 taxi companies
operating more than 38,000 taxi cars.
</P>
<P>
Dazhong Taxi, which now boasts 110 million yuan of assets and
operates 2,400 taxi cars, has built up its fame as a trustworthy
company for its higher standards of service. Per-taxi net profit
of the company was 30,000 yuan last year, triple the city's
average level.
</P>
<P>
Closer trans-regional cooperation will be an unavoidable trend
with the establishment of a link-up network of expressways in
China by the year 2005, and the numerous taxi companies in
Shanghai will eventually be merged into ten major group companies,
Yang predicted.
</P>
<P>
Dazhong Taxi purchased and took over 300 taxi cars of several
small taxi companies in 1996, and will double the figure this
year, Yang added.
</P>
<P>
According to Yang, his company has also established Dazhong Taxi
chain companies in ten other Chinese cities, with 3,500 taxi cars
in operation.
</P>
<P>
Dazhong Taxi plans to bring the number of its chain taxi
companies outside Shanghai to 24 which operate a total of 6,000
taxi cars by the turn of this century.
</P>
<P>
"Under market economic system, an enterprise should not be
confined to any regional limits and but extend its cope of
business wherever markets exist," Yang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
