<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Scientists Use Computers to Help Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli scientists have used
computers and electronics to help disabled persons in their daily
life, The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem College of Technology (JCT) has developed a
series of impressive devices to aid the disabled -- a computerized
devices that synthesizes Hebrew text into recognizable speech, an
infra-red navigation system that helps the blind find their way,
and a Hebrew-speaking, easily programmable clock that wakes blind
children by speaking their own names.
</P>
<P>
The infra-red navigation system to use infra-red ceiling
transmitters to help the blind navigate their way inside
buildings. Building locations are coded into digital values, and
the codes are transmitted from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
The user wears a portable receiving unit, which senses the
closest beam and echoes the signal into a building location. He
then hears spoken announcements about where he is and is warned
to watch out for stairs or other potential dangers.
</P>
<P>
"We use technology to help disabled people to function better,
not only to make them more independent but to increase their
self-confidence and allow them to contribute to society," said
Emil Dere, founder and managing director of JCT's four-year-old,
non-profit Center of Technology for the Handicapped.
</P>
<P>
Foreseeing the advantage of applying technology to improve the
lives of the disabled, Dere, an electronics innovator, set up
the center at JCT.
</P>
<P>
Having designed customized devices to help many of the 70
pupils at Keren Or, a Jerusalem school for multi-handicapped
brain-damaged, mute and blind children, the center is now ready
to make its clinical resources available anywhere in Israel and
in the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
