<HEADLINE> S. Africa Face Serious Drug Trafficking Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A drug war has erupted
between gansters in Johannesburg and Nigerian drug dealers in the
city, in which 28 Nigerians have been kidnapped, South African
Justice Minister Dullah Omar said at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerians had organized themselves into heavily armed
teams to protect their key drug dealers and it was feared that
there could be gang battles in the streets, local daily City
Press quoted Omar as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the South Africa Institute of International Affairs
workshop on the drug trade in Southern Africa, Omar said South
Africa's integration into the world community had created far to
much space for well-organized crime and drug syndicates.
</P>
<P>
The latest sophisticated electronic tools and modern
information technology had also made the drug traffickers evade
police and customs possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
South africa, accessible by land, sea and air, has been used
as a conduit for smuggling hashish, heroin and opium to the
international market, Omar said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to South Africa, Namibia, Kenya, Swaziland,
Angola, Tanzania and Ugnada are now also on the major cocaine
trafficking routes.
</P>
<P>
"International cooperation is of vital importance to combat
drug trafficking and money laundering effectively, Omar stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to Omar, addicts in South Africa now consume an
estimated 70 percent of the world's Mandrax.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months of 1996, police had sized about
300,000 Mandrax tablets and about 77 kg of cocaine and 1,325 LSD
tablets, but this was only about 10 to 15 percent of all drugs
smuggled into South Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
The South African Narcotics Bureau estimated that during 1996,
136 world drug syndicates, out of a total of about 480, operated
in South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
