<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Explain Defense Review to Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Japan will soon detail to its
neighbors its just-worked-out interim report of the ongoing
reviews of the 1978 guidelines for defense cooperation with the
United States, Kyodo News Service reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We should get neighboring countries to rid themselves of their
sense of uncertainty over what Japan would do in a crisis. We will
fully explain to the neighboring countries, particularly to China
and South Korea," Kyodo quoted a senior Foreign Ministry official
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Japan would send the Defense Agency's Defense Policy Bureau
chief Masahiro Akiyama to China in mid-June, and another official
to South Korea, to explain the review of the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
The country would try to assure China that the guidelines
review did not target any particular country, Kyodo said, quoting
Foreign Ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
Japan and the U.S released a seven-page interim report on their
review of defense guidelines in Hawaii on Saturday, vowing to
strengthen cooperation on defense in peacetime, during armed
attacks on Japan and in emergencies in areas surrounding
Japan. The review will be finalized in September.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, in emergencies, Japan would provide
additional land and facilities to U.S. forces and allow
U.S. military to use the country's Self-Defense Forces' (SDF)
bases, civilian airports and seaports.
</P>
<P>
The SDF would also provide logistic support to U.S. military
forces on Japanese territory as well as "on the high seas and in
international airspace surrounding Japan," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The strengthened defense cooperation between Japan and the
U.S. has caused concerns among Japan's neighboring countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
