<HEADLINE> Iran Refutes Turkey's Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Iran has refuted Turkey's claims on
alleged assistance to its anti-government guerrillas of Turkey's
Kurdish Workers Party (PKK), an official report said here today.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA said that the Foreign
Ministry issued a statement in response to the Turkish allegations
made by Erol Ozkasnak, secretary general of the Turkish armed
forces general staff.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish general had charged Friday that Turkey's neighbors
including Iran have a hand in providing missiles and logistic
training to the PKK guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Mohammadi, spokesman for the Iranian Foreign Ministry
said "the allegations of this Turkish military official is in
contradiction with the announced policies of Turkey on the
good bilateral relations and their expansion."
</P>
<P>
He stated that Iran has concentrated efforts in the direction
of promoting security cooperation between the two countries and
that the results of such cooperation have been thoroughly
constructive.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that such "irresponsible and selfish statements
by certain Turkish military officials over the past few months"
are the prime indications of attempts by those opposed to
Iran-Turkey friendship in order to "create an atmosphere of
suspicion between the two nations" and "pursue their own
objectives in the region,"
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also expressed regret over reports containing
similar charges carried by some Turkish newspapers, and said "the
clamor in the Turkish press is neither in the interest of good
neighborly relations nor in the direction of promotion of
cooperation among all in the region." 
</P>
