<HEADLINE> Zambian Official Calls for Discouraging Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambian health deputy minister
Nkandu Luo has called for discouraging the public from smoking.
</P>
<P>
Luo said here on Sunday that the best that could be done is to
do anything possible to discourage the public from smoking
because tobacco growing is a lucrative business and could not be
stopped.
</P>
<P>
Sunday mail today quoted her as saying that smokers not only
endanger their lives but that of the people around them as well.
</P>
<P>
She also said tobacco killed over three million people per
year worldwide and Zambia is no exception to this morbidity.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Joseph Pobee, World Health Organization (WHO)
representative, complained that in developing countries
cigarettes and other tobacco products are marketed without the
warning that cigarettes are bad for one's health.
</P>
<P>
He also said that in many countries, the prices of cigarettes
have been increased to deter would-be smokers from adopting the
habit and try and get smokers to stop the practice. 
</P>
