<HEADLINE> Israel Revokes PNA Security Chief's VIP Card </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Israel has decided to cancel the
VIP card of a senior Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
official whom it holds responsible for the murder of three
Palestinians alleged to have sold land to Israelis, Israel Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The special VIP card enables the holder to enter Israel from
the West Bank and Gaza Strip freely and to cross into Jordan and
back with no restrictions.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted PNA officials as saying that the VIP card
for Tawfik Tirawi, head of the Palestinian General Security
Service in the West Bank, would expire today.
</P>
<P>
Israeli General Security Service head Ami Ayalon told PNA
President Yasser Arafat about the cancellation of Tirawi's pass
at a meeting in Ramallah in the West Bank Friday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials would not comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
Tirawi called the move "an attack on Palestinian
sovereignty," and denied any connection to the killings.
</P>
<P>
"I was not involved in any way in the killings of the land
dealers. This is absolutely untrue," Tirawi said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Israel issued a warrant for the arrest of one of
Tirawi's subordinates, Hussein Saadeh, who is the head of
Palestinian intelligence in Ramallah, Jerusalem police spokesman
Shmuel Ben-Ruby said.
</P>
<P>
In all, three Palestinians suspected of selling land to Jews
have been killed in the past month and the kidnaping of a
fourth was foiled at the last minute by Israeli police.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police say they were holding at least four PNA
security officials involved in the killing of three Arabs
suspected of selling land to Jews.
</P>
<P>
However, Amin Hindi, head of Palestinian intelligence in the
Gaza Strip, denied PNA involvement in the deaths of the land
dealers, saying "Israel has no proof of any sort that the PNA
intelligence is involved in the killings." 
</P>
</TEXT>
