<HEADLINE> US, EU Allow Egypt To Break Mideast Peace Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU) peace
envoy said that the United States and the EU will give Egypt two
weeks for reviving the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks stalled
for three months since mid-March, reported local English daily,
The Jerusalem Post, today.
</P>
<P>
EU special Mideast envoy Miguel Moratinos said that after the
Egypt's move, the U.S. and the EU will formulate a new strategy.
But no details were given.
</P>
<P>
The envoy made the remarks in an interview with the
pro-government newspaper following his visit to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos traveled to Washington last week for consultations
with officials of the Clinton Administration on how to bring the
deadlocked peace process back on track. He met with U.S. Middle
East peace coordinator Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was "very, very satisfied" with the joint
American-EU efforts to promote the peace march, and the EU's
"special relationship with Washington "has been reinforced."
</P>
<P>
"Coordination is going well between the Europeans, the
Americans, and the Egyptians," said Moratinos, who returned to
Israel Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"If there is no breakthrough as a result of the Egyptian
initiative, the American administration will be fully involved
and will try to do something, along with the EU... If there is
something, (the EU leadership) will applaud. If not, we'll
react."
</P>
<P>
He said that the meeting between Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat and Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak Saturday could indicate how the Egyptian effort is
progressing.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, in his lightning visit to Cairo Saturday, the second
in four days, discussed with Mubarak Egypt's recent mediation
efforts to break the impasse in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
According to diplomatic sources, Egypt and the PNA were
working on a five-point plan including a freeze on any change in
the status of Jerusalem and a ban on a Jewish settlement in the
West Bank for a "sufficient period of time."
</P>
<P>
Moratinos emphasized that Palestinian security cooperation and
Israeli concessions on building at Har Homa and in settlements
form the crux of a peace package. 
</P>
</TEXT>
