<HEADLINE> Three African States Propose Secret Ballot Over Ivory Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The three Southern African states
proposing the downlisting of the African elephant from appendix
one to appendix two will ask for a secret ballot during the
forthcoming convention on international trade in endangered
species meeting in a bid to protect delegates from intimidation
by countries opposing the lifting of the ivory trade ban, the
Sunday Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
This comes in the wake of a looming confrontation between the
United States and some heavily western-backed animal rights
groups against Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe over downlisting
proposals as the wildlife issue assumes both political and
economic significance.
</P>
<P>
At a just ended pre-conference meeting held in Darwendale of
Zimbabwe, many of the African countries pledged their support to
Zimbabwe and the two other regional states over their joint
proposal which they described as "well researched, well prepared
and well presented".
</P>
<P>
But sources who attended the meeting said it would be
difficult to "openly" vote against the powerful western and
U.S.-backed forces for fear of losing aid and other bilateral
assistance hence moves to have a secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe are currently lobbying for
support for the downlisting of the African elephant from appendix
i to appendix ii, which allows limited trade in the mammal
products.
</P>
<P>
They request for the lift of the trade ban, put in place in
1989, to enable them to dispose ivory stockpiles worth several
millions of dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
