<DOCNO> XIE19970608.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Fujian Reports Expectedly Good Economic Indicators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The overall economic situation is
good in east China's Fujian Province, according to a leading
provincial official.
</P>
<P>
"The major economic indicators have turned out to be just as
good as expected," Chen Mingyi, secretary of the provincial
committee of the Communist Party of China, said at a regular
meeting of the provincial people's congress.
</P>
<P>
He said that the acreage of early rice this year is expected to
reach 536,000 ha, 638.6 ha more than last year.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's provincial gross domestic product rose 14.5 percent in
the first quarter, while its industrial output value was up 17.7
percent on a yearly basis to 60 billion yuan, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
An analysis shows that state-owned enterprises and enterprises
with the State holding the controlling stakes generated 18.17
billion yuan in output value in the first three months, up 5.5
percent over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that the industrial production-to-sales ratio was
approximately 94.8 percent between January and March, down 1.49
percentage points from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's exports surged 31.2 percent to more than 3.155 billion
US dollars in the first quarter, Chen said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the fiscal and financial sector performed
well in the first three months, with quarterly fiscal income up
26.4 percent year-on-year to 7.59 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Construction of key projects went smoothly in the first quarter,
during which total investments in fixed assets were up 10.2
percent, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, price rises in Fujian continued to slow
down between January and March, up merely 1.1 percent on an annual
basis. Average incomes of urban residents were 10.9 percent more
than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Despite the generally satisfactory economic indicators, Chen
said that problems and difficulties still exist in the economic
work of Fujian, citing amounting difficulties in the effort to
reduce the losses and increase profits of the state-owned
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
