<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Steel Consumption Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The annual consumption growth of
steel in India was around 4.4 percent during 1989-95, lower than
the gross domestic product (GDP) growth of 5.5 percent during the
same period, according to the latest study by the Confederation of
Indian Industry (CII).
</P>
<P>
The elasticity of steel consumption with respect to GDP is
approximately 0.8 percent. The decline in consumption of steel in
relation to GDP growth was constraining growth of steel industry.
There is a need to increase the elasticity factor of steel with
respect to GDP to around 1.5 to 2.0 for the revival of growth, the
study said.
</P>
<P>
The suggested strategy on steel consumption, according to the
study, included development of sectors that are intensive in
consumption of steel such as infrastructure, construction
industry, capital goods and consumer durables. There has been a
serious shortfall in investment in major infrastructure sector
(power, ports, roads and railways) during the eighth five year
plan period (1992-1997).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
