<HEADLINE> Canada's Sun Life Invests in Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Sun Life Assurance Co. is
more interested in Chinese children than insurance professionals,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Sun life recently donated one million US dollars to enhance
education and health care for children in China's developing areas,
company chairman John McNeil said.
</P>
<P>
Part of the money will be used to build a primary school in
Chongqing, southwest China. The school is expected to accommodate
1,200 students. Part will go to the Canada China Child Health
Foundation to set up children's medical clinics in Chongqing and
northwestern Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The primary school and medical clinics are expected to open by
1999.
</P>
<P>
McNeil said that the donations indicated Sun Life's commitment
to the future of Chinese youth and the nation.
</P>
<P>
Overseas insurance companies normally make charitable donations
to obtain operating licenses in China. Many of them choose to
donate money to train Chinese insurance professionals.
</P>
<P>
Currently, only two overseas life insurance companies --
American International Group and Canada's Manulife -- are allowed
to sell life insurance policies in China. Both use conventional
retail sales methods.
</P>
<P>
McNeil said that Sun Life is attracted by China's potential
growth in private and group life insurance.
</P>
<P>
Headquartered in Toronto, Sun Life operates in about 80
countries and regions worldwide. 
</P>
