<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Gradually Cut Interest Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government has
decided to go for gradual reduction in interest rate to make the
local industry competitive.
</P>
<P>
"The interest rate will be gradually brought down from an
average rate of 17.5 percent to 12 percent in the next financial
year," Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz told the press Saturday at a
pre-budget briefing.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, who will present the first budget of the government led
by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on June 13, said the crux of the
economic revival package is to control increase in prices and
provide employment opportunities to youth.
</P>
<P>
"The budget is being framed to provide maximum job opportunity
and arrest the upward spiral of basic commodities' prices," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that within one or two years, the economy would be
put on the right track.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said the government is poised to announce
decisions to help generate revenue and cut down expenditure,
including downsizing of the government.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, confident of reviving the economy, said less taxes,
freezing electricity tariff at present level and a stable exchange
rate would be the key parameters of the next budget.  
</P>
