<HEADLINE> Fire Kills Over 60, Injures 200 in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Over 60 people were killed and
200 others injured when a huge fire broke out at the Thanjavur
temple in Tamil Nadu of southern India Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today said that the consecration of the
1,000-year-old Brahadeeswarar temple, popularly known as the big
temple, at Thanjavur town was scheduled to be held Sunday after a
gap of nearly 17 years.
</P>
<P>
The fire was caused when some airborne crackers fell into the
temple and ignited the oil vessels and the pandal, which was
already dry due to extreme hot temperature.
</P>
<P>
Officials said most of the victims died due to stampede caused
by panic. Many fell down and could not get up as they were
trampled by those who were rushing out. The burning pandal also
collapsed, torching many people to death.
</P>
<P>
The toll might go up as many of the injured were rushed to
private hospitals in serious condition, they said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people had gathered in the temple complex to
witness the last pre-consecration ritual when the pandal caught
fire and instantly spread.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
