<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Imports From India Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's volume of imports from
India has risen tremendously last year, according to local news
paper reports.
</P>
<P>
The value of Sri Lanka's total imports from India in 1996 was
over 550 million US dollars while Sri Lanka's exports to India
stood at only 50 million US dollars, leaving the trade imbalance
largely in favor of India.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have agreed recently to examine the trade imbalance
with India looking into the possibility of removing non-tariff
barriers while Sri Lanka should expand its product base, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
India said that India had opened its huge market for Sri Lankan
products. In the process, India had reduced tariffs on 81 items in
favor of Sri Lanka. Now they are studying the possibility of
adding more items to this list.
</P>
<P>
On the subject of investment opportunities available in the two
countries, both sides agreed that a greater alliance network
should be created through joint marketing and buy-back
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
India has also agreed to help Sri Lanka upgrade its
infrastructure facilities and to promote tourism between the two
countries, the reports added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
