<HEADLINE> Thailand to Provide Better Services for Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's immigration and tourist
police are gearing up to provide better services and safety for
tourists in line with the government's scheme to revitalize
tourism.
</P>
<P>
The improvement of service, which will be put into force within
six months, will start from the Bangkok international airport --
the country's main gateway.
</P>
<P>
Foreign and local visitors will see a much better immigration
service at the beginning of August, Pol Maj-Gen Ekachai Warunprapa
of the Immigration Bureau was quoted today by local press as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The first improvement in the pipeline is the bureau's plan to
introduce a "fast track" immigration service for first and
business class visitors.
</P>
<P>
Airlines will be asked to send a list of air travelers in
advance so that immigration officers at the airport can process
the paperwork before they actually turn up at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Along with the fast track service, the present visa and
passport examination at immigration booths at the airport will
also be revamped.
</P>
<P>
In addition, "group check" will be introduced to allow visitors
traveling in groups to pass through the immigration checkpoint
more quickly and conveniently.
</P>
<P>
Pol Col Wuth Liptapallop, deputy commander of the tourist
police, said measures are also being prepared by his agency to
provide better care for the country's visitors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970608.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Strives To Accomplish Self-Sufficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The core of our prosperity relies primarily on a more open
mind-set," said Xie Shijie, secretary of the Sichuan Provincial
Committee of the Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing became a separate municipality in the spring. Like
Beijing, its municipal government is now accountable to the
central government, instead of provincial rules.
</P>
<P>
Xie went on to say that six million people from rural areas
moved to eastern coastal cities for jobs and brought back about 30
billion yuan (about 3.6 billion US dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
As many as 340,000 small business owners returned home with
money, technology and managerial expertise, launching thousands
of township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"We must also seize the opportunity of coastal capital flowing
westward,otherwise we will lag behind, " Xie noted.
</P>
<P>
About 4,400 solely-foreign-owned and joint ventures have
settled in Sichuan, he added, bringing about two billion US
dollars of investment. Seven foreign banks have offices in
provincial capital Chengdu.
</P>
<P>
The vast potential market, cheap labor, natural resources and
strong industry are boons to the emerging economy.
</P>
<P>
But the separation of Chongqing from Sichuan is expected to
disperse capital flow. Besides, the municipality has a large
Yangtze River port, 270 billion Cubic meters of natural gas and
excellent infrastructure facilities spawned by the ongoing Three
Gorges Dam project.
</P>
<P>
To avoid problems, Sichuan sought its own outlet by building a
10,000-ton container port in Luzhou. A railway links Neijiang in
Sichuan, and Kunming in Yunnan Province will provide an indirect
sea outlet for Sichuan commodities.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, some cities, like Mianyang, Deyang and Leshan,
hold promise as provincial high technology center, a specialty
chemical base and tourist haven within the Chengdu economic
circle.
</P>
<P>
A plan to form a new industrialized civilization has been
outlined, in which the province will pin its hopes on six pillar
industries: information technology, machinery and metallurgy,
building materials, food processing, chemicals and
pharmaceuticals, and tourism.
</P>
<P>
The province has also prepared 91.8 billion yuan (11 billion US
Dollars) this year to expand 37 profitable enterprises and
large-scale infrastructure and energy projects, a record in
fixed-asset investment, Xie said.
</P>
<P>
To improve the investment environment, the landlocked province
is building expressways, highways, railroads and airports. By the
year 2000, up to 1,000 km of expressways will be completed, and
four railways will switch to electric power from coal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970608.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Police to Use Internet to Fight Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Thai police authorities are
launching a program to use the Internet to fight crimes in a bid
to improve their crime suppression efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Under the program which will be in full operation in 1999,
people could report complaints and crimes by e-mail, while the
latest crime suppression details, such as suspects' identities,
missing vehicles and warrants for wanted criminals, are also
provided on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the program is expected to come on-line
later this year, which would provide general information,
including telephone numbers, about the (Bangkok) Metropolitan
Police Bureau (MPB) as well as basic guidelines on how to avoid
becoming a victim.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that information supplied to the police
via e-main will remain confidential and only police offers know
the password.
</P>
<P>
The police authorities believed that the Internet-based system
would be effective in fighting crimes, as the use of the Internet
is becoming popular around Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The system will also be linked with the International Criminal
Police Organization (Interpol) to facilitate cooperation on
international anti-crime cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
