<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Mexican President Hails Hong Kong's Return to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The return of Hong Kong to
China is an important step to definitively finish with colonialism
in the world and opens a new chapter in the total decolonization
of the world process.
</P>
<P>
These were the comments made by the former Mexican President,
Luis Echeverria Alvarez, during an interview with Xinhua here
today.
</P>
<P>
The former Mexican president, now dedicated to promoting
studies about the developing countries, underscored that the
return of Hong Kong to China is of a great importance not only for
China, but also for all the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"As a friend I have always been of China, I reiterate my
conviction that the Opium War was an unjust war against that
country, a brother of the developing countries, and that it was
only a pretext to establish the basis for the British expansionism
and colonialism in that region," said Echeverria.
</P>
<P>
"China will recover, after 150 years of arduous and tenacious
struggle, the exercise of its sovereignty over Hong Kong, which is
a just action in the world and represents a great triumph for the
Chinese people and government," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I never doubted -- knowing the character and the history of
the heroic Chinese people -- that it finally would achieve the
victory, integrating Hong Kong to its territory."
</P>
<P>
Echeverria said of the "one country, two systems" theory, that
it was a "very sensible formula for the modernization promoted by
our friend Deng Xiaoping."
</P>
<P>
Echeverria, a lawyer and an old friend of the Chinese people,
has visited China three times and maintains a deep feeling of
friendship toward China.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five years ago the then head of the Mexican state
adopted important measures directed to support the People's
Republic of China in the recovery of the place it deserved in the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He also decided to break relations with Taiwan authorities and
establish diplomatic relations with China.
</P>
<P>
He traveled to China in 1973 to become the first Mexican chief
of state to visit the ancient country in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
