<HEADLINE> Philippine Muslim Rebels Facing Breakup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 8 (Xinhua) -- The Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) rebels in the southern Philippines are breaking up due to
internal squabbles, the Sunday Chronicle reported here today.
</P>
<P>
Major General Romeo Padiernos, chief of the Southern Command of
the Armed Forces of the Philippines, was quoted as saying that the
MILF is splitting into three factions according to their regional
attachments.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 Maranao members, disillusioned with the present
MILF leadership, have pulled out from the MILF central head office
of Camp Abubakar, while another 1,200 Tausog rebels have already
left Matanog Camp in Maguindanao, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The disillusioned rebels are reported to be setting up another
rebel group of a still undetermined ideological orientation,
prompting Padiernos to place all military forces in the nearby
areas on full alert.
</P>
<P>
Padiernos confirmed that the Maranaos are blaming MILF vice
chair for military affairs Al Haj Murad for the heavy Maranao
casualties in the clashes between MILF and government troops.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a faction broken away in 1978 from the mainstream
Moro National Liberation Front which signed a final peace
agreement with the government last year.
</P>
<P>
The 12,000-member insurgency group is scheduled to hold the
fifth round of low-level talks with the government on June 17-18.
The two sides achieved little progress in their first four rounds
of talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
