<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Banks Off to Good Start in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Eleven overseas banks have been
granted licenses to operate in the Chinese capital, today's China
Daily quoted an official of the Beijing branch of the People's
Bank of China (PBC) as saying.
</P>
<P>
It said that nine of them have actually started operation,
adding that Japan's Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi was the first
overseas bank to open a branch in Beijing in July 1995.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is attractive to overseas banks for its distinct status
and promising market, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March, outstanding loans by the overseas banks
had reached 730 million US dollars, up 223 percent from a year
ago. Meanwhile, savings grew 33.6 percent to 410 million US
dollars and the banks' assets soared 92 percent to 1.76 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some of the banks have begun earning profits despite the short
period of operation, the official said, adding that in the first
quarter of this year the banks made a combined 370,000 US dollars
in profits.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corp., which set up a branch
here in August 1995, is among the profitable banks. It raked in
profits last year and was profitable in the first quarter of this
year, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of overseas banks are applying for business licenses in
Beijing and even more financial institutions have applied to open
representative offices, the PBC Beijing official said.
</P>
<P>
Official record shows that more than 200 overseas financial
institutions have opened offices in Beijing, about half of the
number of offices set up in China by overseas banks.
</P>
<P>
As China's political, cultural and international exchange
center, Beijing is a strategic city for overseas financial
institutions to expand their business networks across the country.
</P>
<P>
Governmental bodies, state banks and many big companies are
headquartered in Beijing, a fact contributing to the city's
importance to overseas firms, experts say.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Beijing is home to Chinese headquarters for many
foreign companies because of its proximity to governmental
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 70 of the world's top 100 banks
have a presence in Beijing while 16 out of the top 20 property
insurers and 10 of the first 20 life insurance companies have
opened offices here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
