<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Strict Regulation to Reduce CD Piracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- A stricter regulation on imported
compact disc production lines took effect last week, reflecting
the country's determination to eliminate piracy, reported today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Co-operation
(Moftec) and the General Administration of Customs regulation
requires licenses for imported CD/VCD production lines since June
1.
</P>
<P>
Moftec's Quota and License Administrative Bureau is responsible
for approving the licenses.
</P>
<P>
Application procedures will differ for domestic and
foreign-funded general trade and processing trade enterprises.
But both kinds of companies, before ordering equipment, must get
permission from the State Press and Publication Administration.
</P>
<P>
Insiders said the new measures show the government's resolve to
fight CD/VCD piracy.
</P>
<P>
"After years of battling copy-right piracy and obscene
publications, we feel it is more urgent to crack down on the
illegal plants than solely purifying the distribution markets," a
Guangdong Province official said.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong previously was the site of most illegal audiovisual
production. But last winter, it swept away more than a dozen
illegal VCD production lines.
</P>
<P>
As the new regulation takes effect, the number of pirated and
pornographic audiovisual products is expected to shrink
significantly in China, industry insiders said.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also affects chemical fertilizers and carbonated
beverages.
</P>
<P>
Under the regulation, companies will need licenses to import 35
kinds of products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
