<DOCNO> XIE19970608.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislation Needed in China for Oil Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 8 (Xinhua) -- China's move to establish a
nationwide oil reserve as part of a strategic oil-supply security
system calls for legislative support, China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for construction of several sea ports capable
of handling large oil tankers. They will be used for loading,
storing and processing imported sulfur-containing crude oil to
ensure sufficient supplies exist in the north and south.
</P>
<P>
China is negotiating with major oil-producing nations in the
Middle East for long-term oil orders as well as financing for
major refineries along China's coast.
</P>
<P>
It also is considering establishing ocean-going oil
transportation fleets. Major petrochemical complexes are expected
to be renovated to increase handling capacity for imported
sulfur-containing crude oil.
</P>
<P>
The reserve plan needs legislative support, central government
planning and a State foundation to be its pillar, and the reserve
is already crucial because the gap between domestic production and
demand is widening, according to Zhu Yu, president of the China
Petrochemical Consulting Corp, the think tank for China
Petrochemical Corp (Sinopec).
</P>
<P>
Despite the relatively slow legislation, petroleum companies
are being mobilized for the system. Presidents of the Sinopec and
the China National Petroleum Corp are visiting major
oil-and-gas-producing nations, especially in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
However, China will continue to need a tiny portion of the
world trade volume, said Zhu, who is also director of the
Sinopec's Petrochemical Planning and Engineering Institute.
</P>
<P>
Efforts for the reserve apparently are increasing the prospects
of foreign governments and enterprises participating more in
petroleum and petrochemical operations in China.
</P>
<P>
Zhu called for legislation authorizing the reserves, saying
that with laws, the community can be mobilized for such an
expensive reserve.
</P>
<P>
"It would be a bit late to officially plan State reserves of
crude oil and oil fuels," he said. "But now is the time to
legislate related plans and measures to quicken the action."
</P>
<P>
Economic growth will force China to import 50 million tons of
crude oil by the year 2000 -- twice the amount imported last
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970608.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Standings at Tour of Italy Cycling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Following are the leading overall
standings after 21 stages Sunday:
</P>
<P>
1. Gotti, 98 hours 29 minutes and 17 seconds
</P>
