<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Consultancy Firms Rush to Shanghai's Pudong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 8 (Xinhua) -- Overseas-funded consultancy firms
are rushing to an emerging financial and trade zone of China's
largest economic center at a rate of more than doubling their
number each year.
</P>
<P>
Official record indicated that the number of operational
overseas-funded consultancy firms in the municipality's Pudong New
Area, which is separated from downtown Shanghai by the Huangpu
River, had reached 257 by the end of April, with a total
investment totaling 168 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
About 20 percent of the firms, which are from the United
States, Britain, Japan, Hong Kong, Taiwan and other countries and
regions, are operated by well-known multi-national corporations.
</P>
<P>
Data provided by the area's bureau for economic and trade
affairs indicate that the number of consultancy firms accounted
for less than one percent of alls sorts of overseas-funded
enterprises in Pudong in 1993. The proportion rose up to eight
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said that the overseas-funded consultancy firms
mainly engage in providing consultancies for matters related to
finances, accounting, taxation, investment, real estate, commerce
and property management.
</P>
<P>
Some of the firms were involved in construction of both the
Nanpu and Yangpu bridges, two major bridges spanning the Huangpu
River built in recent years, a bureau official said.
</P>
<P>
The consultancy firms have on the one hand brought into China
advanced expertise and on the other hand made big profits out of
the area's economic boom.
</P>
<P>
Conservative estimates have put the business income of Earnest
and Young's Shanghai firm at more than 100 million yuan (some 12
million US dollars) for fiscal year 1995-1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
