<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opens Consulate General in Munich </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MUNICH, Germany, June 7 (Xinhua) -- China today opened a
consulate general in the southern German city of Munich, the
second Chinese consulate general in the country after the one in
the northern port city of Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
In a message of congratulations to the event read out by
Chinese ambassador to Germany, Lu Qiutian, at the opening
ceremony, Chinese leader Li Ruihuan, who is currently on a
seven-day official goodwill visit to Germany, said he hopes the
new consulate general will make positive contributions to
strengthening the friendship and cooperation between the Chinese
and German peoples, and between China and Bavaria.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), made the first stop of
his visit to Germany in Munich, capital of the German state of
Bavaria, on Thursday. He left here Saturday afternoon for Berlin
to continue his visit.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the consulate general,
Chinese Ambassador Lu said the Sino-German relations have made
great progress since they established diplomatic ties in 1972.
</P>
<P>
Because both are countries of great importance in their
regions, the smooth development of the bilateral ties between
China and Germany will not only benefit the two peoples, but also
benefit the world peace and stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Bavaria has been playing a very important role in
the development of Sino-German relations, Lu expressed the
confidence that the opening of a Chinese consulate general in
Munich will strengthen the relations between the two countries as
well as between China and Bavaria, and will deepen the
understanding and friendship between the Chinese and German
peoples.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the opening ceremony, vice-premier of the
Bavaria state, Hans Zehetmair said it is of great importance for
Bavaria and China to expand their good relations. The
establishment of the Chinese consulate general in Munich could
make great contributions to this end.
</P>
<P>
Munich is the third largest city of Germany with a population
of over one million. It is also the center for new industries,
where many large companies, like Siemens, BMW and Allianz base
their headquarters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
