<HEADLINE> Dustmen in Athens Resume Work After Week-Long Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Dustmen today began clearing tons of
rubbish from the capital city of Athens and port city of Piraeus
after ending a week-long strike for higher pay and renewal of
permanent employment contracts.
</P>
<P>
The workstoppage by dustmen in the two cities, which began on
Monday, has left about 10,000 tons of uncollected rubbish piled up
on streets, posing a health risk.
</P>
<P>
The decision to return work was taken late last night after
agreement was reached during talks between local government
organization workers' representatives and Interior Undersecretary
Lambros Papadimas.
</P>
<P>
Dustmen have walked out 24 times in the past 16 months because
of their continuing row with the Interior Ministry over contract
employment.
</P>
<P>
The last strike by dustmen took place last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
