<HEADLINE> Central European Countries Pledge Help for Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from 16 Central
European countries ended their two-day meeting here on Saturday,
pledging to assist Bosnia's reconstruction efforts.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the Central European Initiative (CEI)
conference agreed to contribute to the strengthening of stability
and reconstruction in Bosnia and called on the international
community to boost its role in the country's peace process, said
Bosnian Foreign Minister Jadranko Prlic, who is also the chairman
of the conference.
</P>
<P>
"It was decided to direct future CEI activities towards the
concentration of assistance for the least developed member
countries of CEI, that is, to those who have the largest need for
enhanced economic development, recovery and reconstruction," he
added.
</P>
<P>
A final document from the conference also called for closer
economic and political cooperation among the member states and
expressed support to the expansion of the European Union and Nato
while pointing out that such process should not cause new
obstacles to cooperation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1989, CEI comprises Albania, Austria, Belarus,
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Bulgaria, Croatia, the Czech Republic,
Hungary, Italy, Macedonia, Moldova, Poland, Romania, Slovakia,
Slovenia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
According to local press, a CEI conference at the level of
prime ministers has been initially scheduled for November in
Sarajevo. enditem

